\b 3.3. Business Rules and Constraints\par
\b0
The current game build is governed by a small number of important business rules and platform constraints.\par

First, the core training loop must preserve continuity between the Call Phase and the on-site mission. Information selected or inferred during the Call Phase must contribute to the incident payload transferred to the next gameplay scene. This is a central rule of the current product because it distinguishes the game from a purely action-driven firefighting simulator.\par

Second, the on-site mission must remain governed by objective-based progression and fail-condition evaluation. The mission system is responsible for determining whether the player is still running the mission, has completed it, or has failed due to time or other mission-specific conditions.\par

Third, the current product must remain usable in offline local execution. The game cannot depend on an external backend, remote dispatch system, or online storage service in order to complete its normal flow.\par

Fourth, player progress and session continuity are local concerns. Profile continuation, pending scene data, pending scenario data, and result-related data must be managed through local persistence mechanisms that fit the current Unity-based implementation.\par

Key constraints include:\par
BR-01: The product is scoped as a single-player desktop application.\par
BR-02: Mission state depends on local scene content and local ScriptableObject configuration.\par
BR-03: Cross-scene flow must remain deterministic enough for repeatable testing and debugging.\par
BR-04: The project scope is limited by capstone time, scene authoring effort, and available gameplay content.\par

