\b 3.4. Core Gameplay Loop\par
\b0
The core gameplay loop of the current FF3D build is the main structure through which the software delivers its training purpose. The loop begins before the player reaches the incident scene and continues until the mission result is displayed.\par

\b 3.4.1. Loop Architecture\par
\b0
The implemented loop can be described as follows:\par

1. Main Menu and local profile selection.\par
2. Loading Scene transition.\par
3. Level and scenario selection.\par
4. Call Phase interaction and report completion.\par
5. Incident payload generation and transfer.\par
6. On-site mission execution.\par
7. Mission result and progression review.\par

This architecture is important because it shows that the current game is not a single-scene action simulation. The software includes both pre-deployment and on-site decision stages, connected through shared data transfer.\par

\b 3.4.2. Loop Invariants\par
\b0
Across scenarios, several loop invariants should remain true in the current build:\par

The player must always pass through a scene-selection or scenario-selection step before entering a mission.\par
The Call Phase must generate data that can be persisted into the next phase of the flow.\par
The on-site mission must always be evaluated through objective and fail-condition logic.\par
The end of the mission must always result in a visible completion or failure state that can be reviewed by the player.\par

\b 3.4.3. Sub-workflows\par
\b0
Within the main gameplay loop, several supporting workflows operate in parallel or as embedded subsystems.\par

The first is the cross-scene flow workflow, in which selected scenario information, pending target scene, incident payload, and call-phase result data are stored and restored through the loading-flow subsystem.\par

The second is the equipment and interaction workflow, in which the player uses first-person interaction, inventory selection, tool usage, and environmental interaction to progress through the mission.\par

The third is the AI support workflow, in which the player can command bot teammates using the bot command system to help with movement, suppression, rescue, breach, isolation, and regroup behaviors.\par

The fourth is the mission evaluation workflow, in which runtime progress is continuously assessed through objective definitions, fail conditions, score updates, and final mission-end presentation.\par

[Insert Figure 3.2. Core gameplay loop and supporting workflows]\par

\b 3.5. Module Functions\par
\b0
The current build is organized into feature-based modules, each responsible for a specific part of the player flow.\par

Main Menu module: handles profile creation, profile continuation, and transition into the main game flow.\par
Loading module: performs controlled scene transition and reads the pending target scene from loading-flow state.\par
Level Select module: allows the player to choose levels and scenarios, and prepares pending scenario and scene data.\par
Call Phase module: presents transcript interaction, follow-up questions, extraction, report completion, and risk assessment.\par
Shared data-flow module: stores and restores local flow data such as pending target scene, player name, pending incident payload, and call-phase result snapshot.\par
On-site gameplay module: handles first-person movement, interaction, equipment use, hazards, victims, and mission logic.\par
Bot command module: enables commandable AI teammates.\par
UI and review module: displays HUD, minimap, dispatch notes, and mission-end result information.\par

