\b 3.7. Functional Requirements\par
\b0
The functional requirements of the current build should be stated in terms of implemented software capability.\par

FR-01: The system shall allow the player to create a new local profile.\par
FR-02: The system shall allow the player to continue an existing local profile.\par
FR-03: The system shall allow the player to select a level and a scenario from the level selection flow.\par
FR-04: The system shall open the corresponding Call Phase scenario based on the selected scenario definition.\par
FR-05: The Call Phase shall allow the player to review transcript content and collect incident information.\par
FR-06: The Call Phase shall allow the player to complete incident report fields and risk assessment.\par
FR-07: The system shall convert the Call Phase result into cross-scene data, including an IncidentWorldSetupPayload and a call-phase result snapshot.\par
FR-08: The loading-flow subsystem shall store and restore pending scene and scenario state between scene transitions.\par
FR-09: The system shall load the configured on-site mission scene after the Call Phase flow is completed.\par
FR-10: The on-site gameplay scene shall support first-person movement and player interaction.\par
FR-11: The player shall be able to use an inventory-based equipment system during the mission.\par
FR-12: The player shall be able to interact with mission-relevant world objects such as doors, windows, hazards, and rescue targets when scene content supports those interactions.\par
FR-13: The mission system shall evaluate runtime objectives and fail conditions.\par
FR-14: The system shall support rescue-related gameplay through victims, rescue targets, and safe-zone delivery logic where configured.\par
FR-15: The system shall support issuing commands to AI bot teammates when commandable bots are present in the mission.\par
FR-16: The game shall display player-facing mission information through HUD and related UI systems.\par
FR-17: The game shall support a minimap or fullscreen map presentation where configured.\par
FR-18: The mission-end flow shall present a visible result state to the player after mission completion or failure.\par
FR-19: The system shall persist local progression and completion-related data where applicable.\par
FR-20: The current build shall remain executable without dependence on internet connectivity or external backend services.\par

[Insert Table 3.5. Functional requirements]\par

\b 3.8. Non-Functional Requirements\par
\b0
In addition to functional correctness, the current game must satisfy several quality-related requirements relevant to a real-time simulation-based Unity application.\par

NFR-01 Performance: The system should maintain responsive first-person interaction and scene transitions appropriate for a desktop training game.\par
NFR-02 Usability: The player should be able to understand the progression flow from menu, to Call Phase, to mission, to result without requiring external system administration.\par
NFR-03 Reliability: Scene transitions and local flow-state restoration should not break the mission loop under normal use.\par
NFR-04 Maintainability: The software should remain organized around feature-based modules and ScriptableObject-driven configuration where appropriate.\par
NFR-05 Extensibility: New scenarios and mission data should be addable through the existing scenario and mission architecture without requiring full redesign of the system.\par
NFR-06 Offline Operability: The main training loop should remain available without network connectivity.\par
NFR-07 Testability: Core systems should remain verifiable through existing EditMode tests and focused runtime validation.\par

These non-functional requirements reflect the current game more accurately than enterprise-oriented concerns such as server scalability, tenant isolation, or cross-platform cloud deployment.\par

